      <div class="verdict" id="quick-verdict">
        <strong>Quick verdict:</strong> The <strong>Sony WH-1000XM5</strong> is the best noise cancelling headphone you can buy in 2026. The ANC is class-leading, the call quality is the clearest of any wireless headphone we have tested, and the 30-hour battery covers a full week of commuting on a single charge. At $399 it is expensive, and the loss of the folding hinge stings — but if you want silence and clarity in one pair of headphones, the XM5 is the one to buy.
      </div>

      <p>Sony launched the WH-1000XM4 in 2020 and it became the default travel headphone for a generation of frequent flyers. The WH-1000XM5, released in 2022, is a bigger redesign than the name suggests — new processors, new microphones, new drivers, and a new frame. We bought the XM5 at retail and put it through 60 days of daily use, including six flights, dozens of calls, and a month of open-office work, to see whether the redesign justifies a $399 purchase.</p>

      <p>This is the long-form version of our recommendation. For a comparison against Bose, Apple, and Sennheiser alternatives, see our <a href="/reviews/best-noise-cancelling-headphones-work/">best noise cancelling headphones for work</a> roundup. If you want a folding design or longer battery, the <a href="/reviews/sennheiser-momentum-4-review/">Sennheiser Momentum 4</a> review covers a strong alternative.</p>

      <h2 id="pros-and-cons">Product Summary</h2>
      <ProductSummary pros={pros} cons={cons} bestFor={bestFor} notFor={notFor} />

      <h2 id="who-should-buy">Who Should Buy This</h2>
      <p>See the summary above for a quick breakdown of who this product is best for and who should skip it.</p>

      <h2 id="detailed-review">Detailed Review</h2>

      <h3>Active Noise Cancellation: Still the Benchmark</h3>
      <p>The defining feature of the WH-1000XM5 is its active noise cancellation, and Sony has pushed the category forward again. The XM5 uses two processors — the new QN1 and the V1 — working with eight microphones (four per ear cup) to sample and cancel ambient noise in real time. The result is the closest thing to silence we have heard from any consumer headphone.</p>

      <p>In our testing, the XM5 reduced airplane cabin rumble to a faint whisper within seconds of turning on ANC. On a six-hour transatlantic flight, the cabin drone essentially disappeared, leaving only the faintest low-frequency hum. In an open office, the XM5 erased keyboard chatter and HVAC noise to the point where coworkers had to wave to get our attention. The Bose QuietComfort Ultra is the only headphone that comes close, and the XM5 edges it out on low-frequency cancellation.</p>

      <p>Sony added an adaptive sound control that switches between presets based on your activity — staying, walking, transit, or running. It uses location and motion data to pick a mode automatically. We found it occasionally too aggressive (it dropped ANC slightly when we walked between rooms), so we disabled it and used full ANC manually. The manual control is one tap away in the Sony Headphones Connect app.</p>

      <h3>Battery Life: 30 Hours That Actually Lasts</h3>
      <p>Sony rates the XM5 at 30 hours with ANC on and 40 hours with ANC off. In real-world testing, with ANC on, LDAC streaming on Android, and a mix of music and calls, we averaged 28 to 30 hours per charge. With ANC off and standard SBC streaming, we pushed past 38 hours. The numbers are honest, not optimistic.</p>

      <p>A three-minute quick charge gives about three hours of playback — enough to finish a flight if you forget to charge before leaving. A full charge from empty takes about 1.5 hours over USB-C. The charging port is on the right ear cup only, which is slightly awkward if your USB-C cable comes from the left side of your desk, but it is a minor complaint.</p>

      <p>The battery is sealed inside the ear cup and not user-replaceable. Sony rates it for several years of daily charge cycles. The older XM4 still holds a charge after three years for users we have spoken to, so we are not concerned about long-term degradation — but it is worth noting that a failed battery means a $399 replacement, not a $30 swap.</p>

      <h3>Call Quality: The Biggest Upgrade Over the XM4</h3>
      <p>The single biggest reason to choose the XM5 over the older XM4 is call quality. The XM5 uses eight microphones and a new bone-conduction sensor to isolate your voice from background noise. Two beamforming mics focus on your mouth, while the others sample ambient noise for cancellation. The result is the clearest call quality of any wireless headphone we have tested.</p>

      <p>We tested the XM5 on Zoom, Microsoft Teams, and phone calls in cafes, on streets, and in a moving car. Callers reported clear, natural voice quality with minimal background bleed even on a busy street corner. The XM4 was acceptable for calls; the XM5 is genuinely good. If you take calls all day, this alone justifies the upgrade.</p>

      <p>The downside is that the microphone array is tuned for voice isolation, not for capturing ambient sound when you want to hear your surroundings. Transparency mode is decent but not as natural as Apple's AirPods Max. For quick conversations, the Speak-to-Chat feature — which pauses music when you start talking and resumes when you stop — works reliably once you calibrate it to your voice level.</p>

      <h3>Comfort and Design: Lighter, But No Folding Hinge</h3>
      <p>The XM5 is lighter than the XM4 (250 g vs 254 g) and the clamping force is gentler, which makes it more comfortable for sessions longer than four hours. The synthetic leather earpads are softer and breathe reasonably well — we wore them for an eight-hour workday without the heat buildup we felt on the Bose QuietComfort 45. The headband has a new synthetic leather wrap that distributes weight more evenly across the top of the head.</p>

      <p>The controversial design choice is the loss of the folding hinge. The XM4 folded inward into a compact case that fit in a small bag; the XM5 only folds flat, which means the included case is larger and less travel-friendly. If you carry your headphones in a backpack, the XM5 case takes up more room. If you carry them in a dedicated headphone sleeve, this matters less. Either way, it is a step backward for travelers who prized the XM4's compactness.</p>

      <p>The build quality is good but feels less premium than the XM4. There is more plastic in the frame, the hinge is less substantial, and the matte finish picks up fingerprints. It is not a flimsy headphone — it survived our 60-day test with no scratches or creaks — but the XM4 felt like a $400 product and the XM5 feels like a $350 one. The trade-off was weight reduction, and most users will accept it.</p>

      <h3>Sound Quality and LDAC: Hi-Res That Matters on Android</h3>
      <p>The XM5 uses new 30mm carbon fiber composite drivers that deliver a slightly more refined sound than the XM4. The signature is still Sony's warm, bass-forward tuning, but the midrange is cleaner and the treble is less sibilant. We compared the XM5 against the Sennheiser Momentum 4 and found the Sennheiser more natural and detailed, but the XM5 is more fun and forgiving on poorly mastered recordings.</p>

      <p>LDAC support is the XM5's hi-res audio feature, streaming at up to 990 kbps over Bluetooth from Android and Windows devices. On LDAC, well-mastered tracks reveal noticeably more detail in the high frequencies and a wider soundstage. The catch is that iPhone owners cannot use LDAC — Apple limits Bluetooth audio to AAC, so the XM5 sounds identical to the XM4 on an iPhone. If you are on Android or Windows, LDAC is a real benefit; if you are on iOS, it is not a reason to upgrade.</p>

      <p>Sony's DSEE Extreme feature upscales compressed audio (Spotify, YouTube) to near-hi-res quality using on-device AI. We could hear a subtle improvement on Spotify tracks — slightly more air around cymbals and vocals — but it is not transformative. Leave it on; it costs no battery and occasionally helps.</p>

      <h3>Touch Controls and Multipoint Bluetooth</h3>
      <p>The XM5 keeps the touch-sensitive right ear cup for playback control. Tap to play or pause, swipe to change volume, double-tap to skip. The controls are responsive indoors, but in cold weather or with gloves, the touch surface stops registering reliably. If you live in a cold climate, this is a real annoyance — physical buttons would have been more reliable.</p>

      <p>Multipoint Bluetooth 5.2 is the feature that makes the XM5 a daily driver. Pair it with two devices — say a Mac and a phone — and music from the Mac pauses automatically when a call comes in on the phone, then resumes when the call ends. We tested this across 60 days and it worked reliably once both devices were paired. The initial setup requires re-pairing if you switch devices often, but day-to-day it is seamless.</p>

      <p>The Sony Headphones Connect app adds a 5-band EQ, ANC tuning, and firmware updates. The EQ is genuinely useful — we boosted the midrange slightly to balance the bass-heavy default tuning. The app is free on iOS and Android, though there is no desktop equivalent. Firmware updates have added features and bug fixes since launch, so it is worth keeping the app installed.</p>

      <h2 id="comparison">How It Compares to the Competition</h2>
      <p>The XM5 competes against the older XM4, the Bose QuietComfort Ultra, the Apple AirPods Max, and the Sennheiser Momentum 4. Here is how they stack up:</p>

