        </tbody>
      </table>

      <p>The <strong>Sony WH-1000XM4</strong> remains a great buy at $278 and frequently drops to $199 on sale. If you want a folding design, better call quality is not a priority, and you can live with slightly weaker ANC, the XM4 is the value pick. See our <a href="/reviews/best-noise-cancelling-headphones-work/">noise cancelling roundup</a> for the full breakdown.</p>

      <p>The <strong>Bose QuietComfort Ultra</strong> has marginally better high-frequency ANC (voices, announcements) but worse battery and call quality. It costs $30 more and does not fold either. Unless you specifically prefer Bose's sound signature, the XM5 is the better all-rounder.</p>

      <p>The <strong>Sennheiser Momentum 4</strong> has double the battery (60 hours) and a more natural, detailed sound, but its ANC is a step behind the XM5 and the call quality is only good, not excellent. If battery life and sound quality matter more than ANC, the Momentum 4 is a strong alternative — see our <a href="/reviews/sennheiser-momentum-4-review/">Sennheiser Momentum 4 review</a> for details.</p>

      <p>The <strong>Apple AirPods Max</strong> has the best transparency mode and the most premium build, but it costs $549, has worse battery (20 hours), and lacks USB-C. For Apple users who prioritize the Apple ecosystem, the AirPods Max is appealing — but for everyone else, the XM5 is the better value.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-advice">Buying Advice</h2>
      <p>Buy the XM5 at full price if you fly regularly, work in an open office, or take calls all day. The combination of class-leading ANC, the clearest call quality of any wireless headphone, and 30-hour battery is unmatched at $399.</p>

      <p>Wait for a sale if you can. Sony runs promotions around Prime Day and Black Friday where the XM5 drops to $299 to $329. We have seen it as low as $279 during clearance events. Set a price alert if you are not in a rush — the XM5 will be discounted heavily once the XM6 launches.</p>

      <p>Skip the XM5 and buy the XM4 if you want a folding design, do not take many calls, and want to save $120. The XM4 is still an excellent headphone and the value champion of the category. The only reasons to pay the premium for the XM5 are ANC, call quality, and comfort.</p>

      <p>Consider the Sennheiser Momentum 4 instead if battery life is your top priority. The Momentum 4 lasts 60 hours on a charge — double the XM5 — and has a more refined sound signature. The trade-off is weaker ANC, but if you work in a quiet environment, the trade is worth it.</p>

      <p>Buy a hard case if you travel. The included soft case is fine for a desk drawer, but it offers no crush protection. A $25 hard case from a third-party brand is the cheapest insurance for a $399 headphone. Pair the XM5 with a <a href="/reviews/best-laptop-stand-desk/">laptop stand</a> and a <a href="/reviews/best-usbc-dock-macbook/">USB-C dock</a> for a clean travel workstation.</p>

